45","about 1268":"circa 1268","1230":"1230","1272":"1272","about 1230":"circa 1230","France":"Frankrijk","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"en":{"ABT 1200–ABT 1272":"about 1200–about 1272","1200–1272":"1200–1272","1230–1272":"1230–1272","1268–Female":"1268–Deceased","–1322":"–1322","–Male":"Deceased","about 1272":"about 1272","ABT 1272":"about 1272","1268":"1268","1322":"1322","ABT 1200":"about 1200","1200":"1200","ABT 1245":"about 1245","about 1268":"about 1268","1230":"1230","1272":"1272","about 1230":"about 1230","France":"France","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Thibaut","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Germanic.  See  <b>Theobald</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thibaut de Beaumont Comte was born about 1200. He married Jeanne de Senlis Dame de Luzarches-la-Motte about 1245. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. He died about 1272, at the age of 74."},"et":{"ABT 1200–ABT 1272":"umbes 1200–umbes 1272","1200–1272":"1200–1272","1230–1272":"1230–1272","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","–1322":"–1322","–Male":"Surnud","about 1272":"umbes 1272","ABT 1272":"umbes 1272","1268":"1268","1322":"1322","ABT 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","ABT 1245":"umbes 1245","about 1268":"umbes 1268","1230":"1230","1272":"1272","about 1230":"umbes 1230","France":"Prantsusmaa","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"ABT 1200–ABT 1272":"noin 1200–noin 1272","1